description.text:
So my wife's Saturn had a little plastic thingy in her door bust again, rendering the power window useless.  The last time we had this $6 part replaced, it cost us $12(!) for the part and another $143 in labor.
Even though I found the part for under $5, I decided it was a crime to pay upwards of $15 for a part that didn't even weigh an ounce.
Time for the printer to come to the rescue again.  
Sorry about the lack of photos - was a hurried job and wanted get everything put back together quickly!

1) Spend all day dismantling the door and panel
2) Print part
3) Install new slider in slide rail
4) Heat up window arm and ball joint (OEM part is a "snap-in" fit) with torch
5) Press hot ball joint into hole in slider part
6) Re-assemble door
&) Working window = Happy wife = more justification for spending $550 on building a reprap!

PRINT IN PLACE TREAD EXPANSION
I have designed a print in place tread set for the Thinkfun Maker Studio sets. The treads are designed to be spaced using the long connectors as a guide. Take the long connector and mark the outside holes as well as the center hole on your box and punch them out. Then print a tread for each side and three spools for each tread. You can design all kinds of vehicles that use treads. I have included a plow for a bulldozer (from a pop-tarts box) and skis to make a snowmobile (from a spaghetti box). You can also use these treads to make a pizza box space shuttle transport and even a Sandcrawler from leftover Amazon boxes. The best part is these treads print in place. There is no fitting them together, they come completely assembled. The more you play with them the smoother they roll! I hope you enjoy these treads and come up with some great expansion designs that use them! UPDATE I have added a new tread design called the rugged version. This version functions that same as the original version but includes extra traction points on the outside of the treads to help them grip the surface they are moving over. Enjoy!

Could not find a replacement glide backplate for my old bathroom drawers at the local hardware store so, hey, why not design and 3D print one!  This plate can be mounted either horizontally or vertically..  Designed this in SolidWorks. The length of each cross is 25.4mm (1.0") and each branch of the cross is 11.35mm (0.445") wide.  There are three slots on each backplate side for a screw or staple.  I beefed up the plate thickness (from 3.3mm to 5mm) as that is what broke on my original backplate.  I added a 2 degree taper for easy attachment to glider.  Pictures include my broken backplate and my 3D printed replacement backplate and the backplate installed with drawer glider.

title: Rail Brace / Impact Device / Finger Stop

description.text:
Totally 3D printable rail accessory, mounts via two screws included in part files that screw into accessory and fit into rail slots (think most cheap vertical foregrips). Accessory is designed mainly to allow you to brace the rail against an object, a wall, some cover, etc; also kind of acts like a finger stop but not really the design intent.
Your mileage may vary on how strong the part is; with HIPS, the screw nub tends to break off first before the actual brace does (which is preferred, you can just keep a bunch of screws with you). Front texture isn't really designed to bite since it was intended to be made in plastic (actually it's cut off a bit for this purpose), main purpose is to give a small extension to the side of the rail to let you pivot the barrel around.
Print 2 screws for each rail brace. Some minor filing on the inside of the weaver rail mount may be helpful to get it to fit, it'll wear on though.
Keep a look out for a few more uploads using the same screw mount system!

title: Modular mountable SD/MicroSD Card box with extract button and auto-close cover

description.text:
Spanish (See below for english):
Necesitaba una caja modular para guardar las tarjetas SD que estuviese integrada en la impresora. Como siempre, quería una solución robusta para proteger bien las tarjetas, esto implicaba insertar completamente la tarjeta en una ranura. Para poder extraerla implementé un mecanismo simple de palanca y botón con una pequeña leva. Así si una tarjeta se inserta en un slot el botón sube automaticamente hacia arriba y simplemente hay que pulsarlo para sacar la tarjeta. Simple pero chulo. Lo he diseñado para que sea fácil de montar/ensamblar. Puedes apilar el numero de modulos que quieras y usar unos tornillos y tuercas M3 para fijarlos. De este modo puedes usar colores diferentes para las tarjetas, a tu elección. También le puse una tapa para que la puedas montar en la impresora si te conviene. Con unos tornillos M3x50 se pueden apilar hasta ocho tarjetas. Elije el tamaño de los tornillos o simplemente córtalos a la medida. A ver si me acuerdo y pongo alguna foto... Las fotos pueden variar ligeramente del diseño real. Los STLs y fuentes FreeCAD siempre están actualizados. Recomiendo usar ABS en vez de PLA por que es más fácil de lijar. Aún así las partes pequeñas como las levas y el botón es mejor hacerlas en PLA. Sé que no es muy bonito, pero mantiene seguras tus tarjetas SD, cumpliendo su propósito original. Recuerda que no soy un artista, solo soy un ñapas. Que te diviertas! Falta por hacer: Nada. Se ha superado el objetivo original del proyecto. Actualización (27-NOV-2015): Añadido un nuevo módulo para un par de tarjetas microSD. El botón y la leva para este módulo son los mismos que para el otro, solo se han añadido dos piezas nuevas: el módulo y la pequeña pieza con forma de '4'. Actualización (16-NOV-2015): Añadida una versión de la tapa para 7 módulos. Acabé poniendo 7 módulos y la tapa de 6 se quedaba corta. Actualización (13-NOV-2015): La tapa no se abría del todo, he recortado un poco para que abra sin problemas y quede fija abierta. Esto solo afecta a la tapa superior. Me he dado cuenta de que la tapa no es simétrica, pero no afecta a su funcionamiento. Trabajo terminado. Actualización (12-NOV-2015): V3 He incrementado el diámetro de los agujeros de las tuercas, y como prometí he añadido una tapa de cierre automático. Imprime la tapa, la leva del muelle, el soporte con muelle y mete un muelle en el agujero. Ensámblalo con un tornillo M3 y ya está. La versión que se muestra aquí es para una configuración de 6 módulos. Añadida traducción a castellano. Corregido soporte, faltaba el agujero del tornillo. Actualización (11-NOV-2015): He recolocado los agujeros, mejorado la leva, y rebajado la altura del slot SD. Ahora las tarjetas reales encajan perfectamente. Se ha incrementado la distancia de expulsion de la tarjeta para que se pueda extraer más fácilmente. Trabajo terminado. (por ahora...) English:
I wanted a modular/stackable SDCard box for mounting it on my printer. As always, I wanted a sturdy solution to keep the cards protected, this implies to insert the card entirelly into a socket. To be able to extract it I implemented a simple plunger/lever mechanism with a small cam. So if a card is inserted in a slot the button automatically turns up and you just push it down to extract the card. Simple but cool. I designed this easy to mount/assemble. You can stack the desired number of slots, then use some M3 screws & nuts to fit them all. This way you can use different colors for different cards, its up to you. Also implemented a mountable cover in case of convenience. With M3x50 screws you can stack up to eight holders. Choose accordingly the screw length or just cut them off. I'll put some pics if I have the time... Pics may be slightly different from the real design. STLs & FreeCAD sources are always up to date. I recommend to use ABS instead of PLA because it is easier to sand. Even so, small parts like cams and button are best made in PLA. I know this isn't very cute, but it keeps secure your SDCards, fulfilling its original purpose. Remember I'm not an artist, I am just a guy that fix things. Happy Boxing!! title: E3D Clip-on Fan Mount and Easy Access Makergear M2 Filament Drive

description.text:
The filament feed part of this "thing" is designed for use with the MakerGear M2 printer, but the fan mount and duct are compatible with many E3D (and clone) hot ends. The feed allows opening from the side in case of jamming.  The fan section uses a single fan to cool both the extruder and the deposited filament.
The feeder provides easy inspection of the drive gear and removal of any errant filament or scrap.  This design also provides firm mounting of metal E3D-style extruders while allowing rapid removal for maintenance.
The fan is clip-on to ensure positive mounting while not impeding cooling of the heatsink from the upper duct.  The lower duct has internal baffles to straighten out the flow of air, reducing the swirling effect of the muffin fan.  Takes just a few seconds to unmount, needs no tools.
Note: I have added the .STEP file for the stationary part of the feeder in case you need to adjust the extruder mount details to suit your specific unit.  I have found slight variation in metal extruder diameters -- makes some of them a tight fit.
Enjoy!

This short piece of tubing MUST be installed or the feeder won't start right! The fan mount assumes a round heatsink, not hexagonal as has been showing up lately.

Fractal Bucky Balls (Truncated Icosahedron).  Calculated by OpenSCAD - all the vertex coords are generated inside the program, using permutations of 3 simple equations with "golden ratio" ((sqrt(5) + 1) / 2).  See OpenSCAD source.

Notes: The "daughter" buckyballs are generated at the point so that a corner of daughter shares a corner of "mother" buckyball. The (mother:daughter) ratio is (1:0.175) which is the minimum ratio that the object be one solid (touched by the edge). I don't think recursive level >= 2 can be generated (limited by time/memory), nor printed out (resolution of printers). Somebody try. :-) The stl files are rotated to make the flat (hexagon) face bottom, resized to radius 50mm (level 0)/100mm (level 1), using Blender. See the comments in the OpenSCAD source about size specs, rotation angle. Fixed data using Microsoft Model Repair service. The pent.stl file and hex.stl files are for dual color filament 3D printers; I used Da Vinci 2.0 Duo, with white and black color. I hate dual color print because of the color contamination, but it's impossible to paint afterwards on level 1 pentagons in black. :-) The 100mm level 1 fractal solid is rather firm, could remove the supports inside using steep file. The upper side was beautiful, but the lower side (on supports) was a bit dirty...

In the OpenSCAD program, the generation equations are beautiful, however, recursive part is dirty; many duplicated codes are there.  This is because the OpenSCAD allows child recursive call (from March 2015 version), but don't allow child's child recursive call.  I'll rewrite if OpenSCAD is improved, or find another way.

title: Sturdy X-Carriage for J-Head with Bowden

description.text:
What you need:
4x LM8UU linear bearing (or similar)
6x M3x25 or M3x30 screw (longer works too)
4x M3 nut
1x M10 or 1/8" pneumatic fitting for the bowden tube
4x Belt attaching clip (from previous carriage) There aren't many lightweight bowden carriages for J-Head on Prusa and the ones I tried weren't as sturdy as I needed. So the logical thing was to design my own carriage and share it here. I have now printed almost 1kg of material with this and I am loving it! It uses four LM8UU bearings that snap in place. You may use zip ties if needed, I didn't. Hot end is fastened with two horizontal M3 screws through the groove and depending on the hotend the pneumatic fitting is either screwed to the hotend or the carriage. The result is a rock solid high performance carriage. Belt attaching holes are spaced 10x20mm, like used in most carriages. If you need a different type belt mount just let me know and I'll design it for you. Update!
I received my authentic J-Heads (they beat all the clones btw) and found out they use M8 hollow screws instead of M10 like the ones on ebay. Pneumatic fittings with M8 thread are hard to find so I altered the design so that the M10 fitting is now threaded to the carriage rather than the hotend. I also added M3 nut traps for the belt.

1. Check which version you need:
-V6 for all hotends that don't take pneumatic fittings directly. (authentic J-Heads)
-V5 for clones with M10 hollow screw that is replaced with the fitting. 2. Print, preferably in ABS, PLA may soften in use.
I used 0.2mm layer height, 50% infill, 3 perimeters. If your print needs cleaning don't drill the two horizontal holes to 3mm, use 2.5mm or don't drill them at all. 3. You need the belt attaching clips that are visible in the photo. I didn't upload them since most of you already have them and Thingiverse has plenty of them too. TIP: With V6 soften the hole with acetone or heat if the fitting is too hard to install. 4. This is explained in the description. Fix the hotend in place with two M3 screws (and pneumatic fitting with V5). Snap bearings in place and attach belt. 5. Go print hella-fast!
